      commentary: `The conclusion drawn from the entire cosmological teaching is not further cosmological information but a practical instruction: be steadfast in yoga. The knowledge of the two paths has served its purpose not as a geography of the afterlife but as a clarification of what matters during life. The yogi who knows these paths is na muhyati — not deluded — about what is worth cultivating.\n\nDelusion — moha — is the central obstacle in the Gita. It is not ignorance in the sense of lacking information; it is the fundamental misperception of what is real and what matters. The one who understands the two paths has dissolved a particular layer of this delusion: the belief that outer circumstances and timing determine one's spiritual trajectory, rather than the inner quality of awareness one has developed.\n\nSarveṣu kāleṣu — at all times — is the final emphasis. Not in retreat, not in special moments, not when the conditions are favorable. Always. This is the whole teaching compressed into two words. The yogi does not have a spiritual life that runs parallel to ordinary life; they have integrated the two until only life remains — permeated throughout by awareness, by practice, by the steadiness of one who knows what does not perish.`
